Date: Wed, 18 Oct 2000 13:26:08 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: The Monitor (Kampala), 18 Oct 2000 [edited

Ebola hemorrhagic Fever Spreads to Soroti, Lira, and Atiak
-----------------------------------------------------------
KAMPALA: Ebola virus has hit displaced persons camps in Gulu district as the
death toll and hospitalised cases continue to rise. Affected camps were
identified as Pabbo, Parabongo and Atiak, all in Kilak county west of Gulu
town. The death toll has reached 37 and at least 82 patients have been
admitted. The BBC yesterday also reported that cases of Ebola fever had been
reported in Amoru and Atiak refugee camps. All day primary and secondary
schools in Gulu municipality have closed after a Senior Five student at Gulu
Senior Secondary School reportedly died of Ebola on Mon 16 Oct 2000.
Yesterday, 4 people were reported to be in critical condition. At least 6
cases were reported from the displaced persons camps.
The district has placed three sub-counties - Bugantira (Aswa county) and
Pece and Bardege (Gulu municipality) - under quarantine, according to a
directive broadcast on Gulu FM radio. All Ebola victims who die are to be
buried by the police, army and prison officers, according to a new directive
also announced over Gulu FM yesterday. Other cases of Ebola fever had been
identified in Amuru and Atiak sub-counties in Kilak county, Gulu and one
case in Agoro in Lamuru county near the Sudan-Uganda border.
Meanwhile, one man has died in Soroti and 5 others were hospitalised in
critical condition following an attack of a haemorrhagic fever believed to
be Ebola fever. A nurse in charge of Alwa health centre, Anayo Maselina,
said she has admitted 4 patients in critical condition. "The 4 are urinating
blood. At first we thought they had cholera but in spite of frantic efforts
to treat them for cholera, the haemorrhage has persisted," she told The
Monitor. In Lira district, a man was left to die at Lira bus park after
passengers feared to touch him believing that he had Ebola fever. The man
reportedly collapsed at about 10:00 am and died at 1:00 pm. The body was
taken to Lira Hospital mortuary, causing a stampede among staff and
patients, and prompting authorities to order the body's immediate burial.
Yesterday's district emergency meeting also learnt that 2 suspected cases of
Ebola fever had been isolated in Lira Hospital.
[Byline: Oketch Bitek & Patrick Elobu Angonu
