Date: Wed, 18 Oct 2000 19:29:18 -0400
From: Pierre Bigras <pbigras@netrover.com>
Source: The Nation, 18 Oct 2000 [edited

Local Concern about Kenyan Response
-----------------------------------
NAIROBI: As international health experts arrive in Uganda to help stem the
spread of Ebola hemorrhagic fever, it is disheartening that Kenya's
response to the fever outbreak seems to be [inadequate. At least one
busload of travellers from Uganda [is reported to have entered the country
without [either an inspection, [or the promised screening against the
virus. Despite assurances that the outbreak has not spilled out of northern
Uganda's Gulu District, where it has killed at least 37 people, it is
imperative that Kenya be on full alert.
Although the World Health Organisation says there is no need to slap travel
restrictions on Uganda, it needs must be noted that Kenya shares a highly
porous border with Uganda. In recent weeks, some 15 000 herders driven out
of their homes by the current drought crossed into northern Uganda and were
reportedly welcomed. Add to these unofficial and even temporary movements
across the border the traffic through the formal border points, and a need
becomes apparent for the country to be vigilant in the event of any
outbreak. However remote the danger of Ebola fever spreading to Kenya, it is
imperative that the country's health authorities put in place a coordinated
strategy for responding to the current crisis.
--
Pierre Bigras
<pbigras@netrover.com>
