Date: Thu, 19 Oct 2000 11:56:07 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: The Age, 19 Oct 2000 [edited

Description of the Earliest Known Ebola Fever Case in Uganda
------------------------------------------------------------
KABEDE OPONG, (Uganda): [A woman was found dead 6 weeks ago in her
round, gray mud hut by her mother and sisters 5 days after she fell ill with
a fever. In keeping with custom, her body was kept in her hut for 2 days to
allow friends and family to take part in the funeral. [The woman's family and
closest friends ritually bathed her body, buried her less than 10 metres
from where she died and then washed their hands in a communal basin as a
sign of unity.
What they did not know was that [the woman was carrying the deadly Ebola
virus. That was on Thu 7 Sep 200. Now, her mother, 3 sisters and 3 other
relatives are dead and the virus has spread across a 25-kilometre radius,
killing at least 39 people and infecting as many as 63 others. How [the woman,
so far the first person known to have contracted Ebola fever in Uganda,
became infected is a mystery. One of [her two children, a 9 month old
boy, died of Ebola fever within days of her funeral, although her 8 year old
son who did not take part in the funeral has so far survived. [The woman, 36,
lived with her mother and sisters in a small compound of 6 thatched huts and
a dilapidated house surrounded by banana trees and rows of corn. She made
her living selling home-brewed cassava beer and corn she ground by hand
inside her 3 metres wide, windowless hut.
Kabede Opong is 7 kilometres from Gulu, a town of 150 000 inhabitants about
360 kilometres north of the capital Kampala. People here do not eat wild
animals, which has been suspected as the source of some past Ebola fever
outbreaks, and [the woman did nothing unusual before she died, except for a
trip to another village to get cassava leaves for brewing. At first,
neighbors thought [she died of dysentery, cholera or any of a number of
illnesses common to the area. "People had fears after the second victim,"
said Justin Okot, a police officer who lived in the compound next to [the
woman.
"It was after the [death of the eighth victim, that we suspected this [to
be a new disease."
More help has arrived today when a team from the World Health Organisation
brought in boxes of protective garments, gloves and a washing machine, as
well as the expertise needed to fight Ebola. "Containment of the outbreak
should not be a problem," said Dr Guenael Rodier, a senior WHO official and
veteran of [several Ebola outbreaks in West Africa. "Simple measures will
avoid the spread of the disease from person to person and that is what we
are going to work on." Rumors abound of cases in other districts of Uganda,
which could either signify a dramatic spread of the disease or just panic.
"There are many rumors that need to be checked," said Dr Rodier. "But it is
clear that if you have no contact with Gulu, then you are unlikely to have
Ebola."
Professor Francis Omaswa, director general of Uganda's medical services,
said reports that two people had died of Ebola in neighboring Kitgum were
false and that the virus was being contained in Gulu district.
[Byline: Chris Tomlinson
