[Ebola virus is transmitted through contact with bodily fluids, such as
mucus, saliva and blood, and can be passed through a simple handshake. Four
days after exposure, flu-like symptoms set in, followed by bloody diarrhoea
and vomiting. About 10 to 15 days later, the victims bleed out through the
nose, mouth and eyes. Blood and other bodily fluids also begin seeping
through the skin, producing painful blisters. Mortality rates of up to 80%
have been recorded in past outbreaks, but the epidemiological data indicate
that close contact is necessary for efficient transmission of the virus from
one person to another. There is little evidence of aerosol transmission.
Dr. Martin Haditsch <martin.haditsch@travel-clinic.at> has pointed out that
a previous report containing the phrase that Ebola virus is a "highly
contagious virus" is misleading. He says that taking into account all the
factors that might contribute to ongoing infections and measures proven to
prohibit infection most cases might be avoided by practising basic hygiene.
It is also important to point out that the host species acting as the
natural reservoir of Ebola virus is unknown. Non-human primates have been
implicated in the origin of some past outbreaks, but susceptibility to
hemorrhagic illness and high mortality suggests that they are not the
primary reservoir host. - Mod.CP
